FIRST Lady Bongi Ngema-Zuma spent quality time with madalas and gogos yesterday. Ngema-Zuma visited elderly residents of Mamelodi, Tshwane, with her BNZ Foundation and the Africa Chinese Women&rsquo; Association.She encouraged the elderly to live healthy lives. One of the gogos, Miriam Ratau (75), said it was a special day for them. &ldquo;We were treated like royalty,&rdquo; said gogo Miriam. The event was held at the Mamelodi YMCA and focused on diabetes awareness. It was inspired by Mandela Month, which encourages citizens to reach out and make a difference in other people&rsquo;s lives.The First Lady joined the gogos and madalas as they were doing their exercises, before talking to them about managing diabetes. &ldquo;My advice to you is to be screened for diabetes now and then,&rdquo; said Ngema-Zuma. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s time to take responsibility for your body and health.&rdquo;She advised the senior citizens to avoid stress. Anita Zhu, president of the Chinese association, said she was impressed.&ldquo;It&rsquo;s amazing that you&rsquo;re still active. You inspire us,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;I&rsquo;d like to be just as active as you are when I&rsquo;m your age.&rdquo;The gogos and madalas were given gifts of blankets, portable radios and food. They were also screened for diabetes and had their blood pressure checked.